ndigenous peoples' movements, and much more. Whether documenting Inka rule or Spanish conquest, three centuries at the center of Spanish empire, or the turbulent politics and cultural vibrancy of the national period, these sources-the majority of which appear in English for the first time-foreground the voices of actors from many different walks of life. Unprecedented in scope, The Bolivia Reader illustrates the historical depth and contemporary challenges of Bolivia in all their complexity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 7aTravel / South America / General.2bisacsh1 aAlbó, Xavier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarragán, Rossana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodale, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQayum, Seemin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomson, Sinclair, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371618zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371618.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles